    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-06-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-06-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="95"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d95">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_LFAWD1">Leahy</persName> Papers: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 95 <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Commanding General, United States Military Mission in the
                        Soviet Union</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_DMGJR1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Deane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Commanding General, Twelfth Army
                        Group</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BGON1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bradley</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-06-25">25 June
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>To <persName corresp="#p_BGON1">Bradley</persName> citing <hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >Shgsd</hi> and to <persName corresp="#p_MGAGC1">General Marshall</persName>
                    for his <gloss target="#t_EyesOnly1">eyes only</gloss> from <persName
                        corresp="#p_DMGJR1">Deane</persName>
                    <gloss target="#t_topsec1">top sec</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_MX1">MX</gloss> 24794.</p>
                <p>As indicated in my <gloss target="#t_M1">M</gloss>–24786, this date,<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d95fn1">Not printed.</note> immediately upon receipt of your <gloss
                        target="#t_S1">S</gloss>–92697<note n="2" xml:id="d95fn2">
                        <ref target="#d91">Document No. 91</ref>.</note> at 2050Z<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d95fn3">i. e., 8:50 p.m., Greenwich Civil Time.</note> on the 23rd,
                    I submitted your request to <persName corresp="#p_AAGAI1">General
                        Antonov</persName>. At the same time the Ambassador submitted the same
                    request to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_V2">Vyshinski</persName> of the Foreign
                        Office<note n="4" xml:id="d95fn4">See <ref target="#d92">document No.
                            92</ref>.</note> who is to have charge of the arrangements in
                    Berlin.</p>
                <p>Sunday, 24 June, there was a victory celebration in Moscow and <pb facs="0258"
                        n="126" xml:id="pg_126"/> no work was done. Thus far we have not had a reply
                    to your request despite constant pressure on our part.</p>
                <p>We fully appreciate the importance of starting on the communication installations
                    and will continue to use every means at our disposal to get Soviet approval.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
